%S A393131 1,1,1,3,1,1,4,1,1,6,1,5,9,1,1,10,12,1,12,1,1,6,1,7,16,1,20,18,1,1,18,
%T A393131 6,1,22,1,1,20,30,1,27,1,8,28,1,4,30,36,1,30,1,1,6,1,1,36,1,44,18,48,
%U A393131 11,40,25,1,42,1,6,36,1,1,46,60,14,42,1,1,12,60,1,52,66,1,20
%N A393131 a(n) = EulerPhi(2*n+1)/A329726(n); index of witnesses for Solovay-Strassen primality test of 2*n+1 as a subgroup of (Z/(2*n+1)Z)*.
%C A393131 a(n) is the index of {a in (Z/(2*n+1)Z)* : a^n == Jacobi(a,2*n+1) (mod 2*n+1)} in (Z/(2*n+1)Z)*.
%C A393131 a((k-1)/2) and A247074(k) = EulerPhi(k)/(Product_{primes p|k} gcd(p-1,k-1)) have the same odd parts, where odd part = A000265.
%C A393131 According to the formula of A329726, for odd k, a((k-1)/2) is odd if and only if k falls into one of these categories:
%C A393131 (a) k = p^e is a prime power;
%C A393131 (b) k is an odd square, with v(k-1,2) > v(p-1,2) for every prime factor p of k, where v(a,2) is the 2-adic valuation of a.
%C A393131 In both cases a((k-1)/2) = EulerPhi(k)/(Product_{primes p|k} gcd(p-1,k-1)) = A247074(k).
%C A393131 Conjecture: Every even number occurs infinitely many times.
%C A393131 On the other hand, if a((k-1)/2) > 1 is odd, then k is necessarily a powerful number (actually either a prime power or a square). Note that the map k -> odd(A247074(k)) is injective on the set of odd powerful numbers (see my notes in the Links section), and so each odd number > 1 can occur at most once in this sequence.
%C A393131 For odd k>1, a((k-1)/2) is a power of 2 (i.e., A329726((k-1)/2) = odd(EulerPhi(k))) if and only if odd(A002322(k)) divides k-1. In other words, a((k-1)/2) is a power of 2 if and only if k is squarefree and odd(p-1) divides k-1 for every prime factor p of k. Those k are listed in A392921.
%H A393131 Jianing Song, <a href="/A393131/b393131.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A393131 Louis Monier, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3975(80)90007-9">Evaluation and comparison of two efficient primality testing algorithms</a>, Theoretical Computer Science, Vol. 11 (1980), pp. 97-108.
%H A393131 Jianing Song, <a href="/A393131/a393131.pdf">Notes on A393131</a>
%H A393131 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler-Jacobi_pseudoprime">Euler-Jacobi pseudoprime</a>.
%H A393131 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solovay%E2%80%93Strassen_primality_test">Solovay-Strassen primality test</a>.
%F A393131 For k=2*n+1, set R := {primes p|k : v(k-1,2)<=v(p-1,2)}, S := {primes p|k : v(k-1,2)>v(p-1,2), v(k,p) odd}, T := {primes p|k : v(k-1,2)>v(p-1,2), v(k,p) even}, then a(n) has 2-adic valuation Sum_{p in R} (v(p-1,2)-v(k-1,2)+1) + l, where l = -1 is both S and T are empty, l = 1 if S is not empty, and l = 0 if S is empty but T is not.
%F A393131 a((p^e-1)/2) = p^(e-1) for odd primes p.
%e A393131 For 2*n+1 = 15, the bases in which 15 is an Euler-Jacobi pseudoprimes are {1,14}, which has index EulerPhi(15)/2 = 4 in (Z/15Z)*.
%e A393131 For 2*n+1 = 21, the bases in which 21 is an Euler-Jacobi pseudoprimes are {1,20}, which has index EulerPhi(21)/2 = 6 in (Z/21Z)*.
%o A393131 (PARI) a(n) = eulerphi(2*n+1)/A329726(n) \\ see A329726 for its program
%Y A393131 Cf. A329726, A033181 (k such that a((k-1)/2)=2), A392377 (k such that a((k^2-1)/2) is even), A394230 (earliest occurrences of even numbers).
%Y A393131 Cf. also A000265, A247074.
